"Zhao M., Held I.M., Lin S.-J., Vecchi G.A.","Simulations of global hurricane climatology, interannual variability, and response to global warming using a 50-km resolution GCM",2009,"Journal of Climate","22","24",,"6653","6678",,,10.1175/2009JCLI3049.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75749091697&partnerID=40&md5=87c7566049f392a4fa985faca47a24b9","University Corporation for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, Colorado, United States; NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, New Jersey, United States","Zhao, M., University Corporation for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, Colorado, United States, NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, New Jersey, United States; Held, I.M., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, New Jersey, United States; Lin, S.-J., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, New Jersey, United States; Vecchi, G.A., NOAA/Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, Princeton, New Jersey, United States","A global atmospheric model with roughly 50-km horizontal grid spacing is used to simulate the interannual variability of tropical cyclones using observed sea surface temperatures (SSTs) as the lower boundary condition. The model's convective parameterization is based on a closure for shallow convection, with much of the deep convection allowed to occur on resolved scales. Four realizations of the period 1981-2005 are generated. The correlation of yearly Atlantic hurricane counts with observations is greater than 0.8 when the model is averaged over the four realizations, supporting the view that the random part of this annual Atlantic hurricane frequency (the part not predictable given the SSTs) is relatively small (<2 hurricanes per year). Correlations with observations are lower in the east, west, and South Pacific (roughly 0.6, 0.5, and 0.3, respectively) and insignificant in the Indian Ocean. The model trends in Northern Hemisphere basin-wide frequency are consistent with the observed trends in the International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS) database. The model generates an upward trend of hurricane frequency in the Atlantic and downward trends in the east and west Pacific over this time frame. The model produces a negative trend in the Southern Hemisphere that is larger than that in the IBTrACS. The same model is used to simulate the response to the SST anomalies generated by coupled models in the World Climate Research Program Coupled Model Intercomparison Project 3 (CMIP3) archive, using the late-twenty-first century in the A1B scenario. Results are presented for SST anomalies computed by averaging over 18 CMIP3 models and from individual realizations from 3 models. A modest reduction of global and Southern Hemisphere tropical cyclone frequency is obtained in each case, but the results in individual Northern Hemisphere basins differ among the models. The vertical shear in the Atlantic Main Development Region (MDR) and the difference between theMDRSST and the tropical mean SST are well correlated with the model's Atlantic storm frequency, both for interannual variability and for the intermodel spread in global warming projections. © 2009 American Meteorological Society.",,"Atlantic hurricane; Coupled Model Intercomparison Project; Coupled models; Deep convection; Global atmospheric models; Horizontal grid spacing; Hurricane frequency; Indian ocean; Interannual variability; Lower boundary conditions; Northern Hemispheres; Random parts; Sea surface temperatures; Shallow convection; Southern Hemisphere; SST anomalies; Time frame; Tropical cyclone; Upward trend; Vertical shear; World climate research programs; Atmospheric temperature; Climatology; Global warming; Hurricanes; Oceanography; Storms; Submarine geophysics; Tropics; Climate models; annual variation; atmospheric modeling; boundary condition; convective system; general circulation model; global warming; hurricane; Northern Hemisphere; parameterization; sea surface temperature; simulation; Southern Hemisphere; temperature anomaly; tropical cyclone; Indian Ocean; Pacific Ocean",,,,,,"Anderson, J., The new GFDL global atmosphere and land model AM2/LM2: Evaluation with prescribed SST simulations (2004) J. Climate, 17, pp. 4641-4673; Bender, M.A., Ginis, I., Kurihara, Y., Numerical simulations of tropical cyclone-ocean interaction with a high-resolution coupled model (1993) J. Geophys. Res., 98, pp. 23 245-23 263; Bengtsson, L., Hodges, K., Esch, M., Tropical cyclones in a T159 resolution global climate model: Comparison with observations and re-analyses (2007) Tellus, 59 A, pp. 396-416; Bengtsson, L., Hodges, K., Esch, M., Keenlyside, N., Kornblueh, L., Luo, J.-J., Yamagata, T., How may tropical cyclones change in a warmer climate (2007) Tellus, 59 A, pp. 539-561; Bretherton, C.S., McCaa, J.R., Grenier, H., A new parameterization for shallow cumulus convection and its application to marine subtropical cloud-topped boundary layers Part I: Description and 1D results (2004) Mon. Wea. Rev., 132, pp. 864-882; Delworth, T., GFDL's CM2 global coupled climate models Part I: Formulation and simulation characteristics (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 643-674; Douville, H., Limitations of time-slice experiments for predicting regional climate change over South Asia (2005) Climate Dyn., 24, pp. 373-391; Emanuel, K.A., The maximum intensity of hurricanes (1988) J. Atmos. Sci., 45, pp. 1143-1155; Emanuel, K.A., Sundararajan, R., Williams, J., Hurricanes and global warming: Results from downscaling IPCC AR4 simulations (2008) Bull. Amer. Meteor. Soc., 89, pp. 347-367; Garner, S., Held, I., Knutson, T., Sirutis, J., The roles of wind shear and thermal stratification in past and projected changes of Atlantic tropical cyclone activity (2009) J. Climate, 22, pp. 4723-4734; Gualdi, S., Scoccimarro, E., Navarra, A., Changes in tropical cyclone activity due to global warming: Results from a high-resolution coupled general circulation model (2008) J. Climate, 21